{"paperId": "0f6ba1ee40b4867269b82135a293bc630b3b20ec", "abstract": "We ask subjects whether they perceive as human-produced a bunch of texts, some of which are actually human-written, while others are automatically generated. We use this data to fine-tune a GPT-2 model to push it to generate more human-like texts, and observe that this fine-tuned model produces texts that are indeed perceived more human-like than the original model. Contextually, we show that our automatic evaluation strategy well correlates with human judgements. We also run a linguistic analysis to unveil the characteristics of human- vs machine-perceived language.", "venue": "IEEE Games Entertainment Media Conference", "year": 2021, "citationCount": 3, "influentialCitationCount": 0, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://aclanthology.org/2021.gem-1.2.pdf", "status": "HYBRID"}, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "This work asks subjects whether they perceive as human-produced a bunch of texts, some of which are actually human-written, while others are automatically generated, and uses this data to fine-tune a GPT-2 model to push it to generate more human-like texts."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [0.043396443128585815, 0.9401296377182007, 0.08683932572603226, -0.23762677609920502, -0.5537245273590088, -0.24623651802539825, 0.48417919874191284, -0.11580706387758255, -0.43666353821754456, 0.05846403166651726, 0.2983784079551697, 0.09903144091367722, 0.18809449672698975, -0.4279749095439911, -0.1887555569410324, 0.2114071547985077, -0.8270398378372192, 0.37187474966049194, -0.1797313094139099, -0.5321707725524902, -0.10516355186700821, -1.3188832998275757, -0.6855450868606567, 0.4766918420791626, 0.9690912365913391, -0.0012718847719952464, -0.03662233054637909, 1.279054880142212, 0.22512708604335785, 0.18223035335540771, -0.06017526239156723, -1.0021623373031616, 0.08092103898525238, -0.16252835094928741, -0.1760796457529068, 0.09450862556695938, 0.22317755222320557, -0.336969226